00:00:13.046 --> 00:00:13.586 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hello everyone.

00:00:14.516 --> 00:00:20.776 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:00:21.276 --> 00:00:22.806 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So I'm Mike Stern.

00:00:22.806 --> 00:00:25.236 A:middle
I'm a User Experience
Evangelist at Apple,

00:00:25.906 --> 00:00:27.706 A:middle
and thank you all for coming.

00:00:27.936 --> 00:00:30.026 A:middle
And sticking around,
after a really long day

00:00:30.026 --> 00:00:31.196 A:middle
of very technical content.

00:00:31.876 --> 00:00:34.736 A:middle
Now, this presentation is going
to be a bit different, right?

00:00:34.736 --> 00:00:35.916 A:middle
This is about design.

00:00:36.426 --> 00:00:40.046 A:middle
And in particular, it's about
designing intuitive interfaces.

00:00:41.016 --> 00:00:43.806 A:middle
I'd like to start with
a little exercise.

00:00:44.686 --> 00:00:47.456 A:middle
Imagine if you will that
you're at your house,

00:00:47.956 --> 00:00:50.696 A:middle
and you're in your kitchen,
and the phone rings.

00:00:51.316 --> 00:00:52.576 A:middle
And the person on the other end

00:00:52.576 --> 00:00:54.816 A:middle
of the line has some really
exciting news for you.

00:00:55.836 --> 00:00:58.516 A:middle
They tell you that
you've won some money.

00:00:59.286 --> 00:01:02.136 A:middle
Not just a little bit of
money, but like a lot of money.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:59.286 --> 00:01:02.136 A:middle
Not just a little bit of
money, but like a lot of money.

00:01:03.306 --> 00:01:06.476 A:middle
And they also tell you that
in order to claim your prize,

00:01:07.156 --> 00:01:10.266 A:middle
you need to call a phone number.

00:01:10.796 --> 00:01:14.326 A:middle
And then, they hang
up the phone.

00:01:15.526 --> 00:01:18.166 A:middle
And so you're sitting there
in your kitchen, and you need

00:01:18.166 --> 00:01:19.776 A:middle
to write down this phone number.

00:01:20.866 --> 00:01:22.976 A:middle
And you need to write down
this phone number before you

00:01:22.976 --> 00:01:23.766 A:middle
forget it.

00:01:24.496 --> 00:01:28.106 A:middle
So you're looking around
for something to write with.

00:01:28.946 --> 00:01:30.306 A:middle
Your iPhone is not
around, right?

00:01:30.716 --> 00:01:32.686 A:middle
And you're casting
around, and you're starting

00:01:32.686 --> 00:01:34.586 A:middle
to get a little panicky
because you really want

00:01:34.586 --> 00:01:37.556 A:middle
to remember this number, and
right before you forget it,

00:01:37.556 --> 00:01:40.446 A:middle
you see a pen and a piece
of paper, and you write

00:01:40.446 --> 00:01:41.166 A:middle
down the phone number.

00:01:42.266 --> 00:01:45.036 A:middle
So that's a pretty
simple scenario, right?

00:01:45.036 --> 00:01:46.426 A:middle
That was the end of
the story, by the way.

00:01:48.036 --> 00:01:49.626 A:middle
[Applause] Thank you, thank
you very much [laughter].

00:01:51.926 --> 00:01:54.706 A:middle
So you had this very clear
objective, which was to write

00:01:54.706 --> 00:01:58.526 A:middle
down this phone number, and you
found a pen and a pad of paper

00:01:58.526 --> 00:02:02.146 A:middle
with which to accomplish
that task, and then you wrote


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:58.526 --> 00:02:02.146 A:middle
with which to accomplish
that task, and then you wrote

00:02:02.146 --> 00:02:03.036 A:middle
down the phone number.

00:02:03.036 --> 00:02:04.686 A:middle
And that was it.

00:02:05.736 --> 00:02:09.686 A:middle
Well, it's not really
quite that simple.

00:02:09.816 --> 00:02:10.675 A:middle
You were under pressure.

00:02:10.746 --> 00:02:12.326 A:middle
You were stressing
out a little bit,

00:02:12.326 --> 00:02:14.856 A:middle
and when you're stressed out,
that can affect your memory.

00:02:15.206 --> 00:02:16.786 A:middle
And it can affect your ability

00:02:16.786 --> 00:02:18.966 A:middle
to perform basic
cognitive tasks,

00:02:19.536 --> 00:02:21.876 A:middle
such as remembering a phone
number and writing it down.

00:02:23.026 --> 00:02:26.036 A:middle
Or picking out a pen from
a bunch of similar objects,

00:02:26.206 --> 00:02:28.226 A:middle
things that look
just like a pen.

00:02:29.556 --> 00:02:31.856 A:middle
And assuming that you can
remember the phone number,

00:02:31.856 --> 00:02:34.696 A:middle
and find the pen and
paper, and write it down,

00:02:34.696 --> 00:02:37.206 A:middle
you have to also consider,
what are all the skills

00:02:37.206 --> 00:02:38.856 A:middle
that are necessary
for you to write?

00:02:39.716 --> 00:02:41.426 A:middle
For starters, writing
involves a lot

00:02:41.426 --> 00:02:43.626 A:middle
of coordination and dexterity.

00:02:44.696 --> 00:02:46.516 A:middle
Just ask a 3-year-old.

00:02:46.766 --> 00:02:48.616 A:middle
They totally suck at
writing [laughter].

00:02:50.946 --> 00:02:55.026 A:middle
And so did all of you, and so
did I, when we were that age.

00:02:55.826 --> 00:03:00.056 A:middle
We went from writing like
this-- to writing like that.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:55.826 --> 00:03:00.056 A:middle
We went from writing like
this-- to writing like that.

00:03:01.286 --> 00:03:04.676 A:middle
Or at least something like this.

00:03:04.876 --> 00:03:07.866 A:middle
Writing with a pen takes
years and years of practice,

00:03:08.186 --> 00:03:11.726 A:middle
and there's all of these small
little skills that you need

00:03:11.726 --> 00:03:13.016 A:middle
to learn along the way.

00:03:13.016 --> 00:03:15.506 A:middle
They're so fluid and
natural to you now,

00:03:15.806 --> 00:03:17.316 A:middle
but they weren't always so easy.

00:03:18.296 --> 00:03:21.416 A:middle
You had to gain the eye-hand
coordination to be able to pick

00:03:21.416 --> 00:03:24.006 A:middle
up and manipulate small objects.

00:03:24.986 --> 00:03:28.266 A:middle
And it took years to learn
how to hold a pen properly,

00:03:28.666 --> 00:03:30.166 A:middle
and position your
wrist on the table,

00:03:30.166 --> 00:03:31.546 A:middle
and your arm for stability.

00:03:32.486 --> 00:03:34.916 A:middle
You had to learn how to
draw basic letter forms.

00:03:35.916 --> 00:03:37.426 A:middle
Or write along a straight line.

00:03:37.506 --> 00:03:39.386 A:middle
You needed to learn the
difference between upper case

00:03:39.386 --> 00:03:40.526 A:middle
and lower case letters.

00:03:41.116 --> 00:03:42.096 A:middle
The list goes on.

00:03:43.366 --> 00:03:46.566 A:middle
But you don't think about any of
those things when you're sitting

00:03:46.566 --> 00:03:48.876 A:middle
in your kitchen and writing
down that phone number.

00:03:48.876 --> 00:03:56.486 A:middle
All of those years of writing
with different types of pens

00:03:56.486 --> 00:03:58.086 A:middle
and pencils and markers

00:03:58.086 --> 00:04:01.676 A:middle
and crayons have given
you this tremendous amount


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.086 --> 00:04:01.676 A:middle
and crayons have given
you this tremendous amount

00:04:01.676 --> 00:04:02.696 A:middle
of muscle memory.

00:04:03.786 --> 00:04:05.536 A:middle
And that muscle memory frees you

00:04:05.536 --> 00:04:07.726 A:middle
to remember something
like a phone number.

00:04:08.956 --> 00:04:11.646 A:middle
If you had to consciously
remember all

00:04:11.646 --> 00:04:14.826 A:middle
of those individual skills,
it would be pretty difficult

00:04:14.886 --> 00:04:21.986 A:middle
for you to have accomplished
that task.

00:04:22.076 --> 00:04:26.396 A:middle
In other words, it's easier
for you to have written down

00:04:26.396 --> 00:04:28.666 A:middle
and remembered that phone
number because the act

00:04:28.666 --> 00:04:30.236 A:middle
of writing is so intuitive.

00:04:31.256 --> 00:04:33.306 A:middle
Using software is no different.

00:04:33.896 --> 00:04:37.016 A:middle
The more apps behave
as we expect them to,

00:04:37.716 --> 00:04:39.316 A:middle
the more intuitive
they are to us.

00:04:39.986 --> 00:04:43.286 A:middle
The more intuitive apps are
to us, the easier it is for us

00:04:43.286 --> 00:04:45.426 A:middle
to concentrate on
our true objectives,

00:04:46.036 --> 00:04:50.056 A:middle
whether that's communicating
with friends, capturing memories

00:04:50.056 --> 00:04:52.566 A:middle
of loved ones, checking
the weather,

00:04:53.676 --> 00:04:55.046 A:middle
or exploring the cosmos.

00:04:56.916 --> 00:05:01.376 A:middle
The very best user interfaces
are so intuitive, so natural,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:56.916 --> 00:05:01.376 A:middle
The very best user interfaces
are so intuitive, so natural,

00:05:01.846 --> 00:05:05.216 A:middle
that they just sort of
disappear, and allow us to focus

00:05:05.216 --> 00:05:07.006 A:middle
on what truly matters.

00:05:07.946 --> 00:05:09.636 A:middle
That is what we call intuitive.

00:05:10.996 --> 00:05:16.056 A:middle
So with that in mind, what
makes an app intuitive?

00:05:17.026 --> 00:05:19.476 A:middle
Well, I've put together
a list of what I believe

00:05:19.526 --> 00:05:21.356 A:middle
to be the top five
characteristics

00:05:21.726 --> 00:05:23.586 A:middle
of intuitive user and
interface designs.

00:05:23.656 --> 00:05:27.046 A:middle
And this is not an
exhaustive list.

00:05:27.586 --> 00:05:31.086 A:middle
We could be here for hours
and hours and hours talking

00:05:31.086 --> 00:05:33.386 A:middle
about all of the things that
makes something intuitive.

00:05:33.436 --> 00:05:35.226 A:middle
We would order pizza,
get drinks,

00:05:35.226 --> 00:05:36.496 A:middle
it would be a lot of fun.

00:05:36.736 --> 00:05:40.666 A:middle
But unfortunately, we don't
have the time for that today.

00:05:40.856 --> 00:05:43.696 A:middle
This list of five things
I think are the most basic

00:05:43.696 --> 00:05:45.266 A:middle
and essential characteristics

00:05:45.636 --> 00:05:48.076 A:middle
of what makes an iOS
or Mac app intuitive.

00:05:48.976 --> 00:05:52.026 A:middle
And I also want to point out up
front here that what's intuitive

00:05:52.026 --> 00:05:55.646 A:middle
to one person may not be
so intuitive to others.

00:05:56.436 --> 00:06:00.126 A:middle
I mean, this is intuitive
if you're an airline pilot.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:56.436 --> 00:06:00.126 A:middle
I mean, this is intuitive
if you're an airline pilot.

00:06:00.896 --> 00:06:03.656 A:middle
Every button, every switch,
every display is there

00:06:03.656 --> 00:06:05.016 A:middle
for a very good reason.

00:06:05.016 --> 00:06:06.276 A:middle
You know where everything is.

00:06:06.776 --> 00:06:07.686 A:middle
Totally natural.

00:06:08.256 --> 00:06:13.766 A:middle
I'm pretty sure this
doesn't work [laughter].

00:06:14.816 --> 00:06:17.746 A:middle
I also want to point out
that these are the most

00:06:17.746 --> 00:06:18.966 A:middle
fundamental things.

00:06:19.026 --> 00:06:20.166 A:middle
The most basic things.

00:06:20.756 --> 00:06:23.066 A:middle
But design is just like
anything else in life.

00:06:23.066 --> 00:06:26.606 A:middle
I mean, sometimes the most basic
things are the most important.

00:06:27.476 --> 00:06:28.676 A:middle
The most consequential.

00:06:29.826 --> 00:06:32.066 A:middle
I've been designing for many
years, and I've seen time

00:06:32.066 --> 00:06:34.296 A:middle
and time again, even
the most seasoned,

00:06:34.396 --> 00:06:38.416 A:middle
the most experienced designers,
who make poor quality designs

00:06:38.446 --> 00:06:40.646 A:middle
because they've lost
sight of the fundamentals.

00:06:42.386 --> 00:06:45.166 A:middle
Now, in order for a
pen to be intuitive,

00:06:45.436 --> 00:06:47.336 A:middle
it needs to get some
very fundamental

00:06:47.636 --> 00:06:49.306 A:middle
or basic things just right.

00:06:50.746 --> 00:06:55.006 A:middle
It needs to be wide enough to
grip firmly, but not so wide

00:06:55.006 --> 00:06:57.086 A:middle
that it can't be
manipulated easily.

00:06:58.166 --> 00:07:02.166 A:middle
If a pen is too thin, or too
wide, it becomes intuitive


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:58.166 --> 00:07:02.166 A:middle
If a pen is too thin, or too
wide, it becomes intuitive

00:07:02.166 --> 00:07:03.756 A:middle
because we become aware of it.

00:07:04.216 --> 00:07:06.926 A:middle
We're trying to think how are
we going to write with this pen?

00:07:06.926 --> 00:07:08.176 A:middle
It doesn't feel quite right.

00:07:09.336 --> 00:07:11.916 A:middle
Or if a pen was too short,

00:07:13.176 --> 00:07:15.216 A:middle
we would not know how
to hold it, right?

00:07:15.216 --> 00:07:17.966 A:middle
We would pick it up with our
fingertips and we'd be writing

00:07:17.966 --> 00:07:19.726 A:middle
with it, it'd be going
all over the place,

00:07:19.726 --> 00:07:22.446 A:middle
and what we write
wouldn't look very good.

00:07:22.526 --> 00:07:24.836 A:middle
We'd be very conscious
of the pen itself.

00:07:25.616 --> 00:07:29.216 A:middle
Or if a pen was too long,
there'd be an opposite problem.

00:07:29.286 --> 00:07:31.536 A:middle
The top of the pen would be
swinging all over the place,

00:07:31.536 --> 00:07:33.746 A:middle
it would feel heavy,
our hands would strain.

00:07:33.996 --> 00:07:36.556 A:middle
Again, we'd be very
conscious of the pen itself.

00:07:36.556 --> 00:07:40.606 A:middle
Designing a pen to have
the right diameter,

00:07:40.906 --> 00:07:43.836 A:middle
or the right length,
seem like pretty basic

00:07:43.836 --> 00:07:45.136 A:middle
and obvious things, right?

00:07:46.366 --> 00:07:50.976 A:middle
Yet, there are countless pen
and app designs that fail

00:07:50.976 --> 00:07:53.136 A:middle
because their designers
have lost sight

00:07:53.516 --> 00:07:54.736 A:middle
of these fundamentals.

00:07:55.296 --> 00:07:58.506 A:middle
And before we dive in, I'll
just say one more thing,

00:07:59.676 --> 00:08:02.266 A:middle
which is that being intuitive
is not very intuitive.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:59.676 --> 00:08:02.266 A:middle
which is that being intuitive
is not very intuitive.

00:08:02.266 --> 00:08:04.766 A:middle
It's actually pretty
difficult to do.

00:08:05.756 --> 00:08:07.166 A:middle
You have to understand the fact

00:08:07.166 --> 00:08:09.656 A:middle
that you're not designing
just for yourself.

00:08:11.056 --> 00:08:12.656 A:middle
You're designing
for other people.

00:08:13.226 --> 00:08:16.206 A:middle
And those people, they don't
know the things that you know.

00:08:16.856 --> 00:08:19.456 A:middle
And they frankly probably
aren't as passionate

00:08:19.456 --> 00:08:21.006 A:middle
about your app as you are.

00:08:22.226 --> 00:08:24.776 A:middle
So they're going to tend
to be a bit impatient,

00:08:25.376 --> 00:08:27.936 A:middle
easily frustrated,
fickle, right?

00:08:28.986 --> 00:08:31.376 A:middle
Designing an intuitive
interface isn't possible

00:08:31.376 --> 00:08:33.765 A:middle
until you can get
out of your own head.

00:08:33.926 --> 00:08:36.726 A:middle
You need to recognize your
own assumptions about things.

00:08:37.056 --> 00:08:39.666 A:middle
About who the people
you're designing for are,

00:08:39.936 --> 00:08:41.346 A:middle
what they're trying
to accomplish.

00:08:41.346 --> 00:08:43.645 A:middle
What they know, what
they don't know.

00:08:44.176 --> 00:08:47.946 A:middle
You need to see clearly, and
you need to hear clearly,

00:08:48.826 --> 00:08:53.066 A:middle
and figure out what it is that
you can do to help them succeed.

00:08:54.366 --> 00:08:57.376 A:middle
If you can do that, you will
have done an amazing thing.

00:08:58.836 --> 00:09:02.556 A:middle
People will appreciate the
fact that you cared enough


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:58.836 --> 00:09:02.556 A:middle
People will appreciate the
fact that you cared enough

00:09:02.556 --> 00:09:04.436 A:middle
to make a great user experience.

00:09:05.396 --> 00:09:07.356 A:middle
So let's dive in, and find

00:09:07.356 --> 00:09:09.196 A:middle
out what the top five
characteristics are,

00:09:09.726 --> 00:09:11.976 A:middle
starting with platform savvy.

00:09:13.696 --> 00:09:15.476 A:middle
Now, let's go back
to pens again.

00:09:15.996 --> 00:09:21.036 A:middle
You see this particular
pen, but you're not going

00:09:21.036 --> 00:09:22.586 A:middle
to have any trouble
writing with it,

00:09:22.586 --> 00:09:25.916 A:middle
because you've used thousands
and thousands of pens before,

00:09:26.676 --> 00:09:29.376 A:middle
and those experiences, writing
with all those different pens,

00:09:29.376 --> 00:09:31.726 A:middle
has given you this
generalized understanding

00:09:32.026 --> 00:09:33.176 A:middle
of how all pens work.

00:09:34.416 --> 00:09:37.196 A:middle
They have shaped your
expectations, and they're going

00:09:37.196 --> 00:09:38.526 A:middle
to influence your behavior.

00:09:39.836 --> 00:09:42.926 A:middle
And when you pick up that
pen, and you write with it,

00:09:43.326 --> 00:09:45.746 A:middle
sure enough, it works
like you expected it to.

00:09:46.416 --> 00:09:48.776 A:middle
And if it didn't, you'd
become frustrated.

00:09:52.516 --> 00:09:54.666 A:middle
When someone uses your
app for the first time,

00:09:55.186 --> 00:09:57.756 A:middle
they do so with all
sorts of expectations

00:09:57.756 --> 00:09:59.306 A:middle
about how it's supposed to work.

00:09:59.306 --> 00:10:03.676 A:middle
Now, these expectations
are formed and affected


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:59.306 --> 00:10:03.676 A:middle
Now, these expectations
are formed and affected

00:10:03.676 --> 00:10:06.596 A:middle
by so many different factors,
but the most important

00:10:06.596 --> 00:10:11.266 A:middle
of those is that individual's
experience using other iOS

00:10:11.266 --> 00:10:12.196 A:middle
or Mac apps.

00:10:12.946 --> 00:10:15.686 A:middle
Those could be ones that
were built into their device

00:10:15.686 --> 00:10:18.566 A:middle
when they purchased it, or
they could be ones that many

00:10:18.566 --> 00:10:22.506 A:middle
of you here today
have made for them.

00:10:22.716 --> 00:10:24.496 A:middle
Now, let's just take
a look at an example.

00:10:25.286 --> 00:10:28.066 A:middle
Swiping a table row to
reveal some actions.

00:10:28.836 --> 00:10:31.086 A:middle
In particular, let's look
at swiping a table row

00:10:31.246 --> 00:10:33.656 A:middle
to reveal some kind of Delete
button or Trash button.

00:10:34.966 --> 00:10:36.336 A:middle
Now, we're all really
familiar with this.

00:10:36.336 --> 00:10:40.516 A:middle
And we first encountered it
maybe with Mail, and we thought,

00:10:40.516 --> 00:10:42.446 A:middle
hey, that's kind of neat, right?

00:10:42.876 --> 00:10:46.456 A:middle
I don't have to go open the
E-mail to see the Trash button

00:10:46.456 --> 00:10:47.446 A:middle
so that I can delete it.

00:10:47.446 --> 00:10:49.156 A:middle
I don't have to go into
some kind of edit mode,

00:10:49.606 --> 00:10:51.836 A:middle
I can just use a gesture
to delete it right away.

00:10:52.816 --> 00:10:54.776 A:middle
And after doing this
a couple of times,

00:10:54.776 --> 00:10:56.736 A:middle
well you got into
the habit of it.

00:10:57.406 --> 00:11:01.406 A:middle
You started to learn to expect
this behavior, this interaction.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:57.406 --> 00:11:01.406 A:middle
You started to learn to expect
this behavior, this interaction.

00:11:02.836 --> 00:11:05.006 A:middle
Now you open Notes for
the very first time.

00:11:05.176 --> 00:11:07.606 A:middle
Never seen this before,
and, you know,

00:11:07.606 --> 00:11:09.496 A:middle
notes looks a little
bit different from Mail,

00:11:09.706 --> 00:11:11.066 A:middle
but not completely different.

00:11:11.826 --> 00:11:12.876 A:middle
There's some similarities.

00:11:13.056 --> 00:11:16.096 A:middle
Like Mail, everything is
arrayed in a scrollable view,

00:11:16.096 --> 00:11:19.296 A:middle
and there's these little gray
lines that separate them,

00:11:20.566 --> 00:11:22.136 A:middle
and you know, you figure

00:11:22.136 --> 00:11:24.786 A:middle
that like E-mail messages,
Notes can be deleted.

00:11:25.776 --> 00:11:30.246 A:middle
So you think to yourself,
well I should be able to swipe

00:11:30.326 --> 00:11:31.656 A:middle
to reveal a Delete button.

00:11:32.476 --> 00:11:34.086 A:middle
You don't even have
to think about it.

00:11:34.546 --> 00:11:36.436 A:middle
In fact, you probably don't.

00:11:37.026 --> 00:11:40.306 A:middle
You try swiping to delete,

00:11:40.306 --> 00:11:44.186 A:middle
because unconsciously you
believe that it should work.

00:11:44.406 --> 00:11:45.886 A:middle
Intuitively, you
think it should work.

00:11:46.706 --> 00:11:48.376 A:middle
And when it does,
you're rewarded

00:11:48.376 --> 00:11:50.516 A:middle
with the outcome
that you expected.

00:11:51.066 --> 00:11:53.226 A:middle
And if it didn't, you
would be frustrated.

00:11:53.686 --> 00:11:55.306 A:middle
You would say "why
did they not do that?"

00:11:55.966 --> 00:11:57.616 A:middle
It makes so much sense, right?

00:11:57.916 --> 00:12:00.736 A:middle
You now have to figure out how
you're going to delete a Note.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:57.916 --> 00:12:00.736 A:middle
You now have to figure out how
you're going to delete a Note.

00:12:02.026 --> 00:12:04.486 A:middle
Swiping to delete is
a platform convention,

00:12:04.486 --> 00:12:06.156 A:middle
and it's among thousands
and thousands

00:12:06.156 --> 00:12:07.916 A:middle
of different platform
conventions

00:12:08.546 --> 00:12:10.706 A:middle
that iOS users have
come to expect.

00:12:12.186 --> 00:12:14.976 A:middle
And not only do they expect
swipe to delete to work

00:12:14.976 --> 00:12:17.466 A:middle
in whatever situation it would
make sense for it to work,

00:12:18.056 --> 00:12:21.976 A:middle
they expect every aspect
of that interaction

00:12:22.316 --> 00:12:24.546 A:middle
to match their previous
experience.

00:12:25.906 --> 00:12:27.836 A:middle
From the sense of
direct manipulation,

00:12:27.836 --> 00:12:31.506 A:middle
to how far they need to drag
the row to reveal the buttons,

00:12:31.966 --> 00:12:34.856 A:middle
maybe even the color and the
size of the button itself.

00:12:35.816 --> 00:12:39.666 A:middle
Any deviations from these
things, no matter how small

00:12:39.666 --> 00:12:43.546 A:middle
or insignificant, could be
incorrectly perceived by them

00:12:43.546 --> 00:12:45.676 A:middle
as being meaningfully different.

00:12:46.536 --> 00:12:49.276 A:middle
Or maybe they just
get this vague sense

00:12:49.376 --> 00:12:50.756 A:middle
that something's
not quite right.

00:12:51.966 --> 00:12:54.176 A:middle
Being consistent with
platform conventions,

00:12:54.476 --> 00:12:56.206 A:middle
in other words, is
a very good thing.

00:12:57.146 --> 00:13:02.286 A:middle
Gestures like pinch, swipe,
pan, tap, they should work


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:57.146 --> 00:13:02.286 A:middle
Gestures like pinch, swipe,
pan, tap, they should work

00:13:02.286 --> 00:13:06.286 A:middle
in very consistent ways, no
matter what type of app we use.

00:13:07.416 --> 00:13:10.886 A:middle
Same is true for controls,
like switches or buttons,

00:13:11.966 --> 00:13:15.936 A:middle
or navigation bars,
tables, and tab bars.

00:13:16.656 --> 00:13:22.596 A:middle
And there are also powerful
conventions about the labels

00:13:22.596 --> 00:13:24.856 A:middle
that we use to convey
certain actions,

00:13:24.856 --> 00:13:26.246 A:middle
or the icons that we use.

00:13:27.076 --> 00:13:30.466 A:middle
Now, this symbol may have
not been immediately familiar

00:13:30.466 --> 00:13:31.796 A:middle
to you the first
time you saw it,

00:13:32.406 --> 00:13:34.666 A:middle
but after you shared
something a couple of times,

00:13:34.666 --> 00:13:38.896 A:middle
you started to get a sense of
what that symbol represents.

00:13:39.846 --> 00:13:42.166 A:middle
You know what kind of
functionality is accessed

00:13:42.586 --> 00:13:44.146 A:middle
by tapping that button.

00:13:44.796 --> 00:13:49.336 A:middle
And these conventions that
exist, at least for iOS and Mac,

00:13:49.796 --> 00:13:51.706 A:middle
are not at all arbitrary.

00:13:53.016 --> 00:13:55.926 A:middle
Swiping to delete
isn't just intuitive

00:13:55.926 --> 00:13:58.706 A:middle
because of the thousands and
thousands of apps that support

00:13:58.706 --> 00:14:00.396 A:middle
that same interaction.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:58.706 --> 00:14:00.396 A:middle
that same interaction.

00:14:01.186 --> 00:14:04.906 A:middle
It's consistent, or
sorry, that's a part of it,

00:14:04.906 --> 00:14:06.036 A:middle
but it's not the whole story.

00:14:06.036 --> 00:14:08.186 A:middle
It's intuitive to
us because it's

00:14:08.186 --> 00:14:11.786 A:middle
like the real-world experiences
that we all share together.

00:14:12.596 --> 00:14:15.656 A:middle
It's like crossing something
off of a list, or you know,

00:14:15.656 --> 00:14:17.366 A:middle
being a 2-year-old
and eating food

00:14:17.366 --> 00:14:18.746 A:middle
and swiping it out of your way.

00:14:18.746 --> 00:14:20.996 A:middle
Right? You don't want it
anymore, so you're going

00:14:20.996 --> 00:14:22.706 A:middle
to swipe to get rid of it.

00:14:23.416 --> 00:14:26.526 A:middle
There is countless, countless
conventions that exist

00:14:26.996 --> 00:14:29.016 A:middle
for any platform for
which you're designing,

00:14:29.016 --> 00:14:31.936 A:middle
and it's important to recognize
what those conventions are,

00:14:32.186 --> 00:14:35.026 A:middle
because that's what
people are going to expect.

00:14:37.056 --> 00:14:39.686 A:middle
But sometimes it's necessary
to break those conventions.

00:14:40.586 --> 00:14:42.766 A:middle
Now, this is actually
not that common,

00:14:43.196 --> 00:14:47.546 A:middle
but maybe you're designing an
app that's never existed before.

00:14:47.666 --> 00:14:49.236 A:middle
A new type of experience.

00:14:49.626 --> 00:14:51.636 A:middle
Or you're designing
for a new type of user,

00:14:51.636 --> 00:14:53.506 A:middle
a new type of scenario,
or context?

00:14:54.336 --> 00:14:57.006 A:middle
Maybe you're just trying
to solve a problem that we,

00:14:57.006 --> 00:15:00.176 A:middle
at Apple, or other, you
guys have never tried


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:57.006 --> 00:15:00.176 A:middle
at Apple, or other, you
guys have never tried

00:15:00.176 --> 00:15:01.576 A:middle
to solve before, right?

00:15:01.576 --> 00:15:03.236 A:middle
So there is no precedent
to follow.

00:15:03.926 --> 00:15:07.876 A:middle
Now, if that's the case for
you, you have a responsibility

00:15:08.666 --> 00:15:12.196 A:middle
to tell people, to inform
them that you have decided

00:15:12.196 --> 00:15:14.766 A:middle
to do something different
with your app.

00:15:15.696 --> 00:15:17.396 A:middle
Now, let's take a
look at an example.

00:15:18.166 --> 00:15:19.236 A:middle
This is Leo's Fortune.

00:15:19.236 --> 00:15:21.106 A:middle
We saw that it won
ADA yesterday.

00:15:21.996 --> 00:15:24.266 A:middle
That's Leo, up there,
on the wooden scale.

00:15:25.126 --> 00:15:27.046 A:middle
Now, as you can see,
there's only one button

00:15:27.046 --> 00:15:28.356 A:middle
on the screen, the Pause button.

00:15:28.356 --> 00:15:31.006 A:middle
Everything else is
done through gestures.

00:15:31.606 --> 00:15:33.976 A:middle
And these gestures,
they're intuitive,

00:15:33.976 --> 00:15:35.386 A:middle
but they're not standard.

00:15:35.436 --> 00:15:36.716 A:middle
They're not really obvious.

00:15:37.736 --> 00:15:39.646 A:middle
So the game provides
